# Ecosystem DET Considerations

This section re-iterates, expands and clarifies specific elements as part of the various referenced standards for use of DETs specifically in the UAS/aviation ecosystem.

Data structures in DRIP are extensible using a registry of aviation keys used in specific sections of the models defined in REF.HME.IFACES. Policy by a CAA and/or DIME MAY add more keys than defined in this document to any structure or be redacted from an RDAP response based on a users credentials.
 
This document standardizes the use of an aviation key (REQUIRED, OPTIONAL or RECOMMENDED) based on the HHIT Entity Type. A `*` character in a given cell of {{tbl-inquiry-keys}}, {{tbl-response-keys}} or {{tbl-rdap-keys}} indicates all HHIT Entity Types for the given normative language column apply.

DIMEs MUST provide to their clients in a public form the following information:

- Additional aviation keys supported in a registration inquiry ({{inquiry-keys}})
- Additional aviation keys clients should expect to be returned in a registration response ({{response-keys}})
- X.509 policies on the field contents of a Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and Certificate
  - Of importance is the Subject contents for a CSR and the HHIT Entity Type being registered as this MAY be affected by CAA policy

## Registration

Registration services are provided via a POST HTTPS interface that consumes and produces either COSE or JOSE objects. It is RECOMMENDED that a DIMEs Authorization certificate is used in HTTPS for server side authentication.

RAAs MUST implement the Oracle as a Service (OaaS) of REF.HME.IFACES. Failure to provide this critical check can, as demonstrated in the example found in the reference, create instances where bogus data is presented to authorized users during lookup attempting to perform enforcement.

DIMEs MUST use the `/.well-known/ome/register` endpoint for interoperable client discovery. See REF.HME.IFACES for implementation details.

